iaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|title=Gold & Platinum search results - Quietdrive|publisher=Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=2015-03-10}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"Deliverance\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n| ''[[Deliverance (Quietdrive album)|Deliverance]]''\n|-\n| 2009\n| \"Jessica\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n| ''[[Close Your Eyes EP]]''\n|-\n| 2010\n| \"Way Out\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n| ''[[Quietdrive (album)|Quietdrive]]''\n|-\n| 2010\n| \"Fading Light\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n| ''[[Quietdrive (album)|Quietdrive]]''\n|-\n| 2012\n| \"Until The End (Acoustic Version)\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n| ''[[Quietdrive (album)|Quietdrive]]''\n|-\n| 2013\n| \"Even When I'm Gone\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n* \"Rise from the Ashes\" (2006), from ''[[When All That's Left Is You]]''\n* \"Jessica\" (2009), from ''Close Your Eyes EP''\n* \"Way Out\" (2010), from ''[[Quietdrive (album)|Quietdrive]]''\n* \"Until the End (Acoustic Version)\" (2011), from ''Quietdrive''\n* \"Body Out of Bed (feat. Liz Akhavan)\" (2013), from ''Quietdrive''\n* \"Lie to me\" (2012), from ''Up Or Down''\n\n===Lyric videos===\n* \"Without My Hands\" (2014), from ''The Ghost Of What You Used To Be''\n* \"On My Own\" (2015), from ''The Ghost Of What You Used To Be''\n\n===Other===\n* Quietdrive's song \"Rise from the Ashes\" appeared on the EA Sports NHL 07 Soundtrack.\n* Quietdrive's song ''Time After Time'' appeared in John Tucker Must Die (2006), Prom Night (2008), and Parks and Recreation (Season 5 episode 16).\n* Quietdrive's songs \"Kissing Your Lips\", \"Deliverance\", and \"Hollywood\" appeared on the Xbox 360 snowboarding game soundtrack, STOKED(2009)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.quietdrivemusic.com Official website] at quietdrivemusic.com\n* {{YouTube|u=Quietdrive|{{PAGENAMEBASE}}}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927015129/http://www.rockbandlounge.com/news/2006-10-quietdrive.asp Quietdrive] on ROCKBANDLOUNGE.COM\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American pop punk groups]]\n[[Category:2002 establishments in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2002]]\n", "name_user": "Stere0123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected link to YouTube profile", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quietdrive"}
{"title_page": "Metropolitan Borough of Bethnal Green", "text_new": "{{Infobox historic subdivision \n| Start=        1743\n| End=          1965\n| Map=          [[File:Metropolitan Borough of Bethnal Green.svg|280px]]\n| map_caption=  Bethnal Green within the County of London\n| Name=         Bethnal Green \n| Origin=       Hamlet in parish of [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]]\n| Government=   Vestry of the Parish of Bethnal Green (1743\u20131900)<br>Bethnal Green Borough Council (1900\u20131965)\n| Status=       [[Civil parishes in England|Civil parish]] (1743\u20131965)<br>[[Poor law parish]] (1834\u20131930)<br>[[Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London|Metropolitan borough]] (1900\u20131965)\n| HQ=           Patriot Square \n| Replace=      [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| Civic=        [[Image:Seal bgreen.png|100px|The Seal of the Metropolitan Borough]]\n| civic_caption= Borough seal \n| Image=        [[File:Former Town Hall, Cambridge Heath Road.jpg|250px|Bethnal Green Town Hall]]\n| image_caption= Bethnal Green Town Hall\n\n|PopulationFirst=       128,183\n|PopulationFirstYear=   1911\n   |AreaFirst=             {{convert|759|acre|km2}}\n   |AreaFirstYear=         1911/1961\n   |DensityFirst=          169/acre\n   |DensityFirstYear=      1911\n\n   |PopulationSecond=      108,194\n   |PopulationSecondYear=  1931\n   |AreaSecond=            {{convert|760|acre|km2}}\n   |AreaSecondYear=        1931\n   |DensitySecond=         142/acre\n   |DensitySecondYear=     1931\n\n   |PopulationLast=        47,078\n   |PopulationLastYear=    1961\n   |AreaLast=              \n   |AreaLastYear=          \n   |DensityLast=           62/acre\n   |DensityLastYear=       1961\n}}\n'''Bethnal Green''' was a [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and a [[Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London|metropolitan borough]] in the [[East End of London|East End]] of [[London]], England.\n\nIt was formed as a civil parish in 1743 from the [[Bethnal Green]] hamlet in [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]] ancient parish,<ref name=vch>{{cite web |title=Bethnal Green - Introduction |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22741 |year=1998 |work=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green | author=T F T Baker (editor) |publisher=British History Online|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> and the church of [[St Matthew, Bethnal Green]] was dedicated in 1746.<ref>{{cite web  |url = http://www.st-matthews.co.uk/history/ |title = History of the Church |publisher    = St Matthew's Church, Bethnal Green |accessdate  = 11 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe vestry became an electing authority to the [[Metropolitan Board of Works]] in 1855 and in 1889 it became part of the [[County of London]]. In the 1900 reform of local government caused by the [[London Government Act 1899]] the parish became a metropolitan borough which bordered [[Metropolitan Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Poplar|Poplar]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Stepney|Stepney]] and [[Metropolitan Borough of Shoreditch|Shoreditch]]. In 1965 it was abolished and merged into the [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]].\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Parish of Bethnal Green 1848.gif|thumb|1848 map of the parish of Bethnal Green|left]]\nUntil 1743 Bethnal Green formed a hamlet within the large parish of [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]].<ref name=vch/> By the 17th century the settlement had achieved a measure of self-government, with its own overseer, [[constable]] and [[beadle]].<ref name=vch2/> It remained a rural area until the beginning of the 18th century, when the expansion of suburban [[London]] saw the development of the [[Brick Lane]] area in the south west of the hamlet.<ref name=pevsner>{{cite book |title=London except the Cities of London and Westminster |series=[[The Buildings of England]] |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1952 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=[[Harmondsworth]] |isbn= |page= |pages=65\u201366 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> The population rapidly increased and in 1743 an [[act of parliament]] constituted Bethnal Green as a separate parish.<ref>{{cite book |last=Youngs |first= Frederic A, Jr. |title=Guide to the Local Administrative Units of England, Vol.I: Southern England |year=1979 |publisher=[[Royal Historical Society]] |location=London |isbn=0-901050-67-9 |page=316}}</ref><ref>''An Act to make Hamlet of Bethnal Green a Separate Parish'' 16 Geo. II c. 28</ref> \nAs well as forming a parish for ecclesiastical purposes, Bethnal Green was also created a [[civil parishes of England|civil parish]] with responsibility for relief of the poor and maintenance of highways. The government of the parish was shared by a [[vestry]], governors of the poor and two separate bodies of trustees. A further board of paving and lighting commissioners were established in 1843.<ref name=vch2>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758 |title=Bethnal Green - Local Government |author= |year=1998 |work=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green |publisher=|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1855 the parish was included within the area of the [[Metropolitan Board of Works]] to which it nominated one member and the various local government bodies were replaced by a single incorporated vestry which consisted of 48 elected vestrymen.<ref name=vch2/>\n\nUnder the [[Metropolis Management Act 1855]] any parish that exceeded 2,000 [[Rates in the United Kingdom|ratepayers]] was to be divided into wards; as such the incorporated vestry of St Matthew Bethnal Green was divided into four wards (electing [[vestrymen]]): No. 1 or East (9), No. 2 or North (9), No. 3 or West (15) and No. 4 or South (15).<ref name=vch2/><ref>{{cite book|title=The London Gazette Issue: 21802|date=20 October 1855|pages=3881\u20133882|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/21802/page/3881|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=H.M.S.O. Boundary Commission Report 1885 Bethnal Green Map|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/maps/sheet/bc_reports_1885/Bethnal_Green_1885|website=Vision of Britain|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1889 the Metropolitan Board was replaced by the [[London County Council]], and Bethnal Green was formally removed from [[Middlesex]] to the new [[County of London]].\n\n== Ecclesiastical parish ==\nBethnal Green was part of the ancient parish of [[St Dunstan]], Stepney in the [[Diocese of London]]; in 1743 the area was split off to form a new parish dedicated to [[St Matthew]].<ref name=\"Bethnal Green1\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22761],'Bethnal Green: The Parish Church', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp. 212-217. Date accessed: 13 March 2014.</ref>\nFrom 1837, as the population of Bethnal Green increased, a number of new parishes were formed:<ref name=\"Bethnal Green2\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22762], 'Bethnal Green: List of Churches', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp. 217-226. Date accessed: 13 March 2014.</ref>\n* '''St John, Bethnal Green''' in 1837\n* '''St Peter, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Andrew, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Philip, Bethnal Green''' in 1843 \n* '''St James the Less, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Bartholomew, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St James the Great, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Jude, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Matthias, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Simon Zelotes, Bethnal Green''' in 1844\n* '''St Thomas, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Paul, Bethnal Green''' in 1865 \n* '''St Barnabas, Bethnal Green''' in 1870\n\nIn addition, as the population of neighbouring Shoreditch increased, parts of Bethnal Green parish were included in the new parish of:\n* '''Holy Trinity, Shoreditch''' in 1866\n\n==Creation of the borough==\nUnder the [[London Government Act 1899]] the various vestries and district boards within the County of London were abolished and replaced by [[Metropolitan boroughs of London|metropolitan borough councils]]. Accordingly, in 1900, a borough council consisting of a mayor, five [[alderman|aldermen]] and 30 councillors replaced the vestry. The boundaries of the borough and parish were realigned at the same time.<ref name=vch2/>\n\nBethnal Green Town Hall in Patriot Square was opened in 1910, and extended in 1936\u20139. The architects were Percy Robinson and William Alban Jones.<ref>http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green|year=1998|publisher=[[Victoria County History]]|pages=190\u2013202|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758|editor=T.F.T. Baker|accessdate=8 April 2013|chapter=Bethnal Green: Local Government}}</ref> In 2010 the building was reopened as a hotel; much of the original art deco interior has been retained.<ref>{{cite web|title=Town Hall Hotel & Apartments|url=http://www.designhotels.com/hotels/europe/unitedkingdom/london/town_hall_hotel|publisher=Design Hotels|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Borough seal==\nThe borough seal depicted a scene based on ''The Beggar's Daughter of Bednall Green'', a poem in [[Thomas Percy (Bishop of Dromore)|Percy]]\u2019s ''[[Reliques of Ancient English Poetry]]'', published in 1765, but probably dating from the era of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]. According to the legend related in the poem, a blind beggar living in Bethnal Green was in fact Henry de Montfort, eldest son of [[Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]], having escaped from the field of the [[Battle of Evesham]] in 1265. His identity was revealed at the wedding feast of his daughter Bessie.<ref>[http://www.eastlondonhistory.com/blind%20beggar.htm ''Blind Beggar of Bethnal Green'' (East London History)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030011746/http://www.eastlondonhistory.com/blind%2Bbeggar.htm |date=2007-10-30 }} accessed 3 Dec 2007</ref> A depiction of the beggar had appeared on the head of the beadle's staff dating from 1690.<ref name=bening>{{cite book |title=London 1900-1964. Armorial Bearings and Regalia of The London County Council, The Corporation of London and The Metropolitan Boroughs |last=Beningfield |first=T J |year=1964 |publisher=E J Burrow |location=London  |pages=49\u201350}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=London's Coats of Arms and The Stories They Tell |last=Crosley |first=Richard |year=1928 |publisher=Robert Scott |location=[[London]] |pages=46\u201349}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Bethnal Green Met. B Ward Map 1916.svg|thumb|A map showing the wards of Bethnal Green Metropolitan Borough as they appeared in 1916.]]\nIn the first election to the borough council, held on 1 November 1900 the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressives]] gained a majority, with 22 of the 30 councillors. The Moderates (supported by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]) formed the 8 member opposition group. The Progressives increased their majority to 24 at the 1903 elections, and in 1906 they won all the seats on the council. The Progressives held the council against the [[Municipal Reform Party]] until 1919 when the [[Labour party (UK)|Labour Party]] gained a majority. Progressives and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]] regained control at the 1925 election, holding power until 1934.\n\nIn 1934, Labour again took control, and from that date held all the seats on the council until the borough's abolition.<ref>Election results as reported in ''The Times'', 3 November 1900; 4 November 1903; 3 November 1906; 2 November 1909; 2 November 1912; 4 November 1919; 4 November 1925; 3 November 1928; 4 November 1931; 3 November 1934; 3 November 1937; 2 November 1945; 7 May 1949; 7 May 1953; 11 May 1956; 8 May 1959; 12 May 1962</ref>\n\nFor parliamentary elections, Bethnal Green was divided into two constituencies in 1885. Each consisted of two wards of the borough and earlier vestry: \n*[[Bethnal Green North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green North East]] (north and east wards)\n*[[Bethnal Green South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green South West]] (south and west wards).\n\nIn 1950, the borough's representation was decreased to a single constituency of [[Bethnal Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green]], which in 1955 was expanded to also include three wards from the neighbouring [[Metropolitan Borough of Hackney]].\n\n==Population and area==\nThe area of the borough was {{convert|760|acre|km2|1}}. It included the districts now known as [[Bethnal Green]], [[Cambridge Heath]] and [[Globe Town]], stretching to include part of the [[Boundary Estate]] in the west and parts of [[Mile End Park]] and [[Victoria Park, London|Victoria Park]] in the east. In the south its boundary stopped just short of [[The Blind Beggar]] pub on [[Whitechapel Road]]. The populations recorded in National Censuses were:\n\n'''Bethnal Green Vestry 1801-1899'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year<ref>Statistical Abstract for London, 1901 (Vol. IV).</ref> \n|| 1801 || 1811 ||1821 || 1831 || 1841 || 1851 || 1861 || 1871 || 1881 || 1891\n|-\n! Population || 22,310|| 33,619||45,676|| 62,018|| 74,088|| 90,193|| 105,101|| 120,104|| 126,961|| 129,132\n|}\n'''Metropolitan Borough 1900-1961'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year<ref>[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_census_page.jsp?u_id=10186353&c_id=10001043 Bethnal Green MetB: Census Tables] at ''Vision of Britain'' accessed on 14 Dec 2006</ref>\n|| 1901 || 1911 || 1921 || 1931 || 1941 || 1951 || 1961 \n|-\n! Population || 129,680|| 128,183 || 117,238 || 108,194 ||<ref>''The census was suspended for [[World War II]]</ref>|| 58,353|| 47,078\n|}\n\n==Second World War==\nDuring [[World War II]], the Borough suffered from heavy aerial bombing. \nIt is estimated that 80&nbsp;tons of bombs fell on this area alone, affecting 21,700 houses, destroying 2,233 and making a further 893 uninhabitable. During the course of the aerial bombardment, 555 people were killed, and 400 were seriously injured.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22753 ''Bethnal Green: Building and Social Conditions from 1915 to 1945'', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp.&nbsp;132\u2013135]</ref>\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120418115717/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10186353 ''MB Bethnal Green'' (A Vision of Britain) archived.]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |chapter=London: Bethnal Green |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=Br0ZAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |title= Municipal Year Book of the United Kingdom for 1907 |editor=[[Robert Donald]] |location=London |publisher=Edward Lloyd |year=1907 }}\n\n{{London Government Act 1963}}\n{{Metropolitan Board of Works}}\n\n{{coord|51.5302|-0.0551|type:adm3rd_dim:5000_region:GB-TWH|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bethnal Green}}\n[[Category:Parishes governed by vestries (Metropolis)]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in London]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1965 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:Districts abolished by the London Government Act 1963]]\n[[Category:Bills of mortality parishes]]\n[[Category:Bethnal Green]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox historic subdivision \n| Start=        1743\n| End=          1965\n| Map=          [[File:Metropolitan Borough of Bethnal Green.svg|280px]]\n| map_caption=  Bethnal Green within the County of London\n| Name=         Bethnal Green \n| Origin=       Hamlet in parish of [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]]\n| Government=   Vestry of the Parish of Bethnal Green (1743\u20131900)<br>Bethnal Green Borough Council (1900\u20131965)\n| Status=       [[Civil parishes in England|Civil parish]] (1743\u20131965)<br>[[Poor law parish]] (1834\u20131930)<br>[[Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London|Metropolitan borough]] (1900\u20131965)\n| HQ=           Patriot Square \n| Replace=      [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]] \n| Civic=        [[Image:Seal bgreen.png|100px|The Seal of the Metropolitan Borough]]\n| civic_caption= Borough seal \n| Image=        [[File:Former Town Hall, Cambridge Heath Road.jpg|250px|Bethnal Green Town Hall]]\n| image_caption= Bethnal Green Town Hall\n\n|PopulationFirst=       128,183\n|PopulationFirstYear=   1911\n   |AreaFirst=             {{convert|759|acre|km2}}\n   |AreaFirstYear=         1911/1961\n   |DensityFirst=          169/acre\n   |DensityFirstYear=      1911\n\n   |PopulationSecond=      108,194\n   |PopulationSecondYear=  1931\n   |AreaSecond=            {{convert|760|acre|km2}}\n   |AreaSecondYear=        1931\n   |DensitySecond=         142/acre\n   |DensitySecondYear=     1931\n\n   |PopulationLast=        47,078\n   |PopulationLastYear=    1961\n   |AreaLast=              \n   |AreaLastYear=          \n   |DensityLast=           62/acre\n   |DensityLastYear=       1961\n}}\n'''Bethnal Green''' was a [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and a [[Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London|metropolitan borough]] in the [[East End of London|East End]] of [[London]], England.\n\nIt was formed as a civil parish in 1743 from the [[Bethnal Green]] hamlet in [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]] ancient parish,<ref name=vch>{{cite web |title=Bethnal Green - Introduction |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22741 |year=1998 |work=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green | author=T F T Baker (editor) |publisher=British History Online|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref> and the church of [[St Matthew, Bethnal Green]] was dedicated in 1746.<ref>{{cite web  |url = http://www.st-matthews.co.uk/history/ |title = History of the Church |publisher    = St Matthew's Church, Bethnal Green |accessdate  = 11 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe vestry became an electing authority to the [[Metropolitan Board of Works]] in 1855 and in 1889 it became part of the [[County of London]]. In the 1900 reform of local government caused by the [[London Government Act 1899]] the parish became a metropolitan borough which bordered [[Metropolitan Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Poplar|Poplar]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Stepney|Stepney]] and [[Metropolitan Borough of Shoreditch|Shoreditch]]. In 1965 it was abolished and merged into the [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]].\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Parish of Bethnal Green 1848.gif|thumb|1848 map of the parish of Bethnal Green|left]]\nUntil 1743 Bethnal Green formed a hamlet within the large parish of [[Stepney (parish)|Stepney]].<ref name=vch/> By the 17th century the settlement had achieved a measure of self-government, with its own overseer, [[constable]] and [[beadle]].<ref name=vch2/> It remained a rural area until the beginning of the 18th century, when the expansion of suburban [[London]] saw the development of the [[Brick Lane]] area in the south west of the hamlet.<ref name=pevsner>{{cite book |title=London except the Cities of London and Westminster |series=[[The Buildings of England]] |last=Pevsner |first=Nikolaus |authorlink=Nikolaus Pevsner |year=1952 |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=[[Harmondsworth]] |isbn= |page= |pages=65\u201366 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> The population rapidly increased and in 1743 an [[act of parliament]] constituted Bethnal Green as a separate parish.<ref>{{cite book |last=Youngs |first= Frederic A, Jr. |title=Guide to the Local Administrative Units of England, Vol.I: Southern England |year=1979 |publisher=[[Royal Historical Society]] |location=London |isbn=0-901050-67-9 |page=316}}</ref><ref>''An Act to make Hamlet of Bethnal Green a Separate Parish'' 16 Geo. II c. 28</ref> \nAs well as forming a parish for ecclesiastical purposes, Bethnal Green was also created a [[civil parishes of England|civil parish]] with responsibility for relief of the poor and maintenance of highways. The government of the parish was shared by a [[vestry]], governors of the poor and two separate bodies of trustees. A further board of paving and lighting commissioners were established in 1843.<ref name=vch2>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758 |title=Bethnal Green - Local Government |author= |year=1998 |work=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green |publisher=|accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 1855 the parish was included within the area of the [[Metropolitan Board of Works]] to which it nominated one member and the various local government bodies were replaced by a single incorporated vestry which consisted of 48 elected vestrymen.<ref name=vch2/>\n\nUnder the [[Metropolis Management Act 1855]] any parish that exceeded 2,000 [[Rates in the United Kingdom|ratepayers]] was to be divided into wards; as such the incorporated vestry of St Matthew Bethnal Green was divided into four wards (electing [[vestrymen]]): No. 1 or East (9), No. 2 or North (9), No. 3 or West (15) and No. 4 or South (15).<ref name=vch2/><ref>{{cite book|title=The London Gazette Issue: 21802|date=20 October 1855|pages=3881\u20133882|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/21802/page/3881|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=H.M.S.O. Boundary Commission Report 1885 Bethnal Green Map|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/maps/sheet/bc_reports_1885/Bethnal_Green_1885|website=Vision of Britain|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1889 the Metropolitan Board was replaced by the [[London County Council]], and Bethnal Green was formally removed from [[Middlesex]] to the new [[County of London]].\n\n== Ecclesiastical parish ==\nBethnal Green was part of the ancient parish of [[St Dunstan]], Stepney in the [[Diocese of London]]; in 1743 the area was split off to form a new parish dedicated to [[St Matthew]].<ref name=\"Bethnal Green1\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22761],'Bethnal Green: The Parish Church', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp. 212-217. Date accessed: 13 March 2014.</ref>\nFrom 1837, as the population of Bethnal Green increased, a number of new parishes were formed:<ref name=\"Bethnal Green2\">[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22762], 'Bethnal Green: List of Churches', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp. 217-226. Date accessed: 13 March 2014.</ref>\n* '''St John, Bethnal Green''' in 1837\n* '''St Peter, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Andrew, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Philip, Bethnal Green''' in 1843 \n* '''St James the Less, Bethnal Green''' in 1843\n* '''St Bartholomew, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St James the Great, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Jude, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Matthias, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Simon Zelotes, Bethnal Green''' in 1844\n* '''St Thomas, Bethnal Green''' in 1844 \n* '''St Paul, Bethnal Green''' in 1865 \n* '''St Barnabas, Bethnal Green''' in 1870\n\nIn addition, as the population of neighbouring Shoreditch increased, parts of Bethnal Green parish were included in the new parish of:\n* '''Holy Trinity, Shoreditch''' in 1866\n\n==Creation of the borough==\nUnder the [[London Government Act 1899]] the various vestries and district boards within the County of London were abolished and replaced by [[Metropolitan boroughs of London|metropolitan borough councils]]. Accordingly, in 1900, a borough council consisting of a mayor, five [[alderman|aldermen]] and 30 councillors replaced the vestry. The boundaries of the borough and parish were realigned at the same time.<ref name=vch2/>\n\nBethnal Green Town Hall in Patriot Square was opened in 1910, and extended in 1936-9. The architects were Percy Robinson and William Alban Jones.<ref>http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green|year=1998|publisher=[[Victoria County History]]|pages=190\u2013202|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22758|editor=T.F.T. Baker|accessdate=8 April 2013|chapter=Bethnal Green: Local Government}}</ref> In 2010 the building was reopened as a hotel; much of the original art deco interior has been retained.<ref>{{cite web|title=Town Hall Hotel & Apartments|url=http://www.designhotels.com/hotels/europe/unitedkingdom/london/town_hall_hotel|publisher=Design Hotels|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Borough seal==\nThe borough seal depicted a scene based on ''The Beggar's Daughter of Bednall Green'', a poem in [[Thomas Percy (Bishop of Dromore)|Percy]]\u2019s ''[[Reliques of Ancient English Poetry]]'', published in 1765, but probably dating from the era of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]]. According to the legend related in the poem, a blind beggar living in Bethnal Green was in fact Henry de Montfort, eldest son of [[Simon de Montfort, 6th Earl of Leicester|Simon de Montfort]], having escaped from the field of the [[Battle of Evesham]] in 1265. His identity was revealed at the wedding feast of his daughter Bessie.<ref>[http://www.eastlondonhistory.com/blind%20beggar.htm ''Blind Beggar of Bethnal Green'' (East London History)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030011746/http://www.eastlondonhistory.com/blind%2Bbeggar.htm |date=2007-10-30 }} accessed 3 Dec 2007</ref> A depiction of the beggar had appeared on the head of the beadle's staff dating from 1690.<ref name=bening>{{cite book |title=London 1900-1964. Armorial Bearings and Regalia of The London County Council, The Corporation of London and The Metropolitan Boroughs |last=Beningfield |first=T J |year=1964 |publisher=E J Burrow |location=London  |pages=49\u201350}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=London's Coats of Arms and The Stories They Tell |last=Crosley |first=Richard |year=1928 |publisher=Robert Scott |location=[[London]] |pages=46\u201349}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Bethnal Green Met. B Ward Map 1916.svg|thumb|A map showing the wards of Bethnal Green Metropolitan Borough as they appeared in 1916.]]\nIn the first election to the borough council, held on 1 November 1900 the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressives]] gained a majority, with 22 of the 30 councillors. The Moderates (supported by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]) formed the 8 member opposition group. The Progressives increased their majority to 24 at the 1903 elections, and in 1906 they won all the seats on the council. The Progressives held the council against the [[Municipal Reform Party]] until 1919 when the [[Labour party (UK)|Labour Party]] gained a majority. Progressives and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberals]] regained control at the 1925 election, holding power until 1934.\n\nIn 1934, Labour again took control, and from that date held all the seats on the council until the borough's abolition.<ref>Election results as reported in ''The Times'', 3 November 1900; 4 November 1903; 3 November 1906; 2 November 1909; 2 November 1912; 4 November 1919; 4 November 1925; 3 November 1928; 4 November 1931; 3 November 1934; 3 November 1937; 2 November 1945; 7 May 1949; 7 May 1953; 11 May 1956; 8 May 1959; 12 May 1962</ref>\n\nFor parliamentary elections, Bethnal Green was divided into two constituencies in 1885. Each consisted of two wards of the borough and earlier vestry: \n*[[Bethnal Green North East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green North East]] (north and east wards)\n*[[Bethnal Green South West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green South West]] (south and west wards).\n\nIn 1950, the borough's representation was decreased to a single constituency of [[Bethnal Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green]], which in 1955 was expanded to also include three wards from the neighbouring [[Metropolitan Borough of Hackney]].\n\n==Population and area==\nThe area of the borough was {{convert|760|acre|km2|1}}. It included the districts now known as [[Bethnal Green]], [[Cambridge Heath]] and [[Globe Town]], stretching to include part of the [[Boundary Estate]] in the west and parts of [[Mile End Park]] and [[Victoria Park, London|Victoria Park]] in the east. In the south its boundary stopped just short of [[The Blind Beggar]] pub on [[Whitechapel Road]]. The populations recorded in National Censuses were:\n\n'''Bethnal Green Vestry 1801-1899'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year<ref>Statistical Abstract for London, 1901 (Vol. IV).</ref> \n|| 1801 || 1811 ||1821 || 1831 || 1841 || 1851 || 1861 || 1871 || 1881 || 1891\n|-\n! Population || 22,310|| 33,619||45,676|| 62,018|| 74,088|| 90,193|| 105,101|| 120,104|| 126,961|| 129,132\n|}\n'''Metropolitan Borough 1900-1961'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Year<ref>[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_census_page.jsp?u_id=10186353&c_id=10001043 Bethnal Green MetB: Census Tables] at ''Vision of Britain'' accessed on 14 Dec 2006</ref>\n|| 1901 || 1911 || 1921 || 1931 || 1941 || 1951 || 1961 \n|-\n! Population || 129,680|| 128,183 || 117,238 || 108,194 ||<ref>''The census was suspended for [[World War II]]</ref>|| 58,353|| 47,078\n|}\n\n==Second World War==\nDuring [[World War II]], the Borough suffered from heavy aerial bombing. \nIt is estimated that 80&nbsp;tons of bombs fell on this area alone, affecting 21,700 houses, destroying 2,233 and making a further 893 uninhabitable. During the course of the aerial bombardment, 555 people were killed, and 400 were seriously injured.<ref>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=22753 ''Bethnal Green: Building and Social Conditions from 1915 to 1945'', A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 11: Stepney, Bethnal Green (1998), pp.&nbsp;132\u2013135]</ref>\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120418115717/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10186353 ''MB Bethnal Green'' (A Vision of Britain) archived.]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |chapter=London: Bethnal Green |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=Br0ZAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA19 |title= Municipal Year Book of the United Kingdom for 1907 |editor=[[Robert Donald]] |location=London |publisher=Edward Lloyd |year=1907 }}\n\n{{London Government Act 1963}}\n{{Metropolitan Board of Works}}\n\n{{coord|51.5302|-0.0551|type:adm3rd_dim:5000_region:GB-TWH|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bethnal Green}}\n[[Category:Parishes governed by vestries (Metropolis)]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan boroughs of the County of London]]\n[[Category:History of the London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]\n[[Category:Former civil parishes in London]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1965 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:Districts abolished by the London Government Act 1963]]\n[[Category:Bills of mortality parishes]]\n[[Category:Bethnal Green]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCreation of the borough:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1936-9 \u2192 1936\u20139", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metropolitan_Borough_of_Bethnal_Green"}
{"title_page": "1638 New Hampshire earthquake", "text_new": "{{Infobox earthquake\n|title= 1638 New Hampshire earthquake\n|pre-1900  = yes\n|local-date= {{Start-date|June 1, 1638}}\n|map2 = {{Location map+ | New Hampshire\n | width= 250\n | float=none\n | caption=\n | places=\n  {{Location map~ | New Hampshire\n  | label=\n  | lat=43.3\n  | long=-71.6\n  | mark=Bullseye1.png\n  | marksize=40\n  | position=top}}\n}}\n|magnitude = 6.5\u20137.0 {{M|w|link=y}}\n|depth=\n|intensity=[[Mercalli intensity scale|IX (''Violent'')]]\n|location={{Coord|43.3|-71.6|display=inline,title}}\n|countries affected = [[British America]]\n|tsunami =\n|casualties =\n}}\nThe '''1638 New Hampshire earthquake''' struck central [[New England]] on June 1 ([[Julian calendar]]).<ref>Sidney Perley. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100209062835/https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/states/events/1638_06_11_hs.php The Earthquake of 1638]. United States Geological Survey</ref> It was the first major [[earthquake]] in New England after the start of European colonization. Modern analysis places its epicenter somewhere near central [[New Hampshire]], and it probably measured between magnitude 6.5 and 7.0 on the [[Richter magnitude scale]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marybarrettdyer.blogspot.ca/2011/09/great-new-england-quake-of-1638.html|title=The great New England quake of 1638|website=marybarrettdyer.blogspot.ca}}</ref> making it the largest earthquake on record in New Hampshire and one of the strongest in the region's history (the [[1663 Charlevoix earthquake]] was probably stronger).\n\n==See also==\n*[[1755 Cape Ann earthquake]]\n*[[List of historical earthquakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1520 Earthquakes in New Hampshire Data (1638\u20131973)] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Earthquakes in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1638 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1638 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Earthquake\n|title= 1638 New Hampshire earthquake\n|pre-1900  = yes\n|local-date= {{Start-date|June 1, 1638}}\n|map2 = {{Location map+ | New Hampshire\n | width= 250\n | float=none\n | caption=\n | places=\n  {{Location map~ | New Hampshire\n  | label=\n  | lat=43.3\n  | long=-71.6\n  | mark=Bullseye1.png\n  | marksize=40\n  | position=top}}\n}}\n|magnitude = 6.5\u20137.0 {{M|w|link=y}}\n|depth=\n|intensity=[[Mercalli intensity scale|IX (''Violent'')]]\n|location={{Coord|43.3|-71.6|display=inline,title}}\n|countries affected = [[British America]]\n|tsunami =\n|casualties =\n}}\nThe '''1638 New Hampshire earthquake''' struck central [[New England]] on June 1 ([[Julian calendar]]).<ref>Sidney Perley. [https://web.archive.org/web/20100209062835/https://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/states/events/1638_06_11_hs.php The Earthquake of 1638]. United States Geological Survey</ref> It was the first major [[earthquake]] in New England after the start of European colonization. Modern analysis places its epicenter somewhere near central [[New Hampshire]], and it probably measured between magnitude 6.5 and 7.0 on the [[Richter magnitude scale]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marybarrettdyer.blogspot.ca/2011/09/great-new-england-quake-of-1638.html|title=The great New England quake of 1638|website=marybarrettdyer.blogspot.ca}}</ref> making it the largest earthquake on record in New Hampshire and one of the strongest in the region's history (the [[1663 Charlevoix earthquake]] was probably stronger).\n\n==See also==\n*[[1755 Cape Ann earthquake]]\n*[[List of historical earthquakes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1520 Earthquakes in New Hampshire Data (1638-1973)] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Earthquakes in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1638 earthquakes]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:1638 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1638_New_Hampshire_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "Peter Wells (athlete)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Peter Wells\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = 1949 08 06 Peter Wells.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- only when absolutely necessary -->\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| headercolor = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name = <!-- if different than name -->\n| full_name = Peter Wells\n| nickname = \n| nationality =  English, New Zealand \n| national_team = \n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1929|05|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Friern Barnet]], London\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1929|05|23|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments = \n| education = Byng Road Council School, [[Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet]]\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| agent = \n| height = {{convert|5|ft|11.5|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| weight = <!-- X kg, X lb, or X st Y lb (automatic conversion) plus optional year and reference -->\n| spouse = \n| life_partner = \n| other_interests = \n| website = {{URL|www.peterwells.co.nz}}\n| country = {{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain<br/>{{flagicon|ENG}} England<br/>{{flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n| sport = Athletics\n| position = \n| disability = \n| disability_class = \n| weight_class = \n| weight_class_type = \n| rank = \n| event = High Jump\n| universityteam = \n| collegeteam = \n| league = \n| league_type = \n| club = \n| team = \n| turnedpro = \n| partner = \n| former_partner = \n| coach = Arthur Gold\n| retired = \n| coaching = \n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = [[1952 Summer Olympics]] [[1956 Summer Olympics]]\n| paralympics = \n| commonwealth = [[1950 British Empire Games]] [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n| highestranking = \n| pb = {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals = \n| medaltemplates-title = \n}}\n'''Peter Wells''' (23 May 1929 \u2013 5 January 2018) was a British-born athlete who competed in the High Jump at the [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952]] and [[1956 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite sports-reference | Peter Wells | https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/peter-wells-1.html| 15 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nHe also represented England at the [[1950 British Empire Games|1950 Empire Games]] in Auckland, and New Zealand at the [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1954 Commonwealth Games]] in Vancouver. After the 1950 Empire Games in Auckland, Wells didn't travel back to England with the rest of the team, preferring to stay and settle in Christchurch, New Zealand. He lived in New Zealand for the rest of his life, apart from a short period in 1952 when he returned to England in order to qualify for the 1952 Summer Olympics. He died in Christchurch on 5 January 2018 after a short illness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deaths.press.co.nz/obituaries/the-press-nz/obituary.aspx?n=peter-wells&pid=187773049|title=Peter Wells death notice|date=9 January 2018|work=[[The Press]]|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/athletics/news/article.cfm?c_id=19&objectid=11979633|title=Athletics NZ weekly roundup 22 January 2018|date=22 January 2018|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/101236222/life-story-humble-olympian-peter-wells-flew-high-and-stayed-grounded|title=Life story: Humble Olympian Peter Wells flew high and stayed grounded|last=Northcott|first=Maddison|date=10 February 2018|work=The Christchurch Press|access-date=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWells was born at [[Friern Barnet]] in North London, the youngest child of Cecil Edward Wells and Ethel Alice Wells (n\u00e9e Cannon). He lived initially in [[Finchley]] before moving at the age of two to [[High Barnet]]. He attended Byng Road Council School, (now called [http://www.fouldsp.org/about-our-school/history Foulds School]), and then went to [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Barnet|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School]] in 1939.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/achievements/national_and_international_honours_list|title=Queen Elizabeth's School - National and international honours list|website=www.qebarnet.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/peters_olympic_memories|title=Peter's Olympic memories|date=2015|website=Queen Elizabeth's School|access-date=18 January 2018}}</ref> \n<!--\n== Early interest in athletics ==\n[[File:193x - Peter Wells Athlete - DOB 1929.05.23.jpg|left|upright=0.65|thumb|Wells as a boy]]\nWells first remembers competing in athletics whilst at Byng Road Council School - participating  in inter-schools\u2019 sports at the Barnet Playing Fields at the bottom of Barnet Hill, in Hertfordshire. The only events at that time were sprints, and Wells was usually able to win his age group.\n\nIn September 1939 Wells went to Queen Elizabeth\u2019s Grammar School for boys, in Barnet, and participated in the annual inter-house athletics, again initially, in short sprints. At some stage he switched to concentrating on high jump and hurdles, in which he represented his school at the County schools\u2019 meeting in 1944, and then the Public Schools\u2019 championships at the White City Stadium, in London. Queen Elizabeth\u2019s had won the team event at those championships in 1939 and there was therefore quite a tradition of athletics at the school. This was probably due mainly to the enthusiasm and coaching of \u201cKlue\u201d (K.L. Woodland), the German language teacher.\n\nHe gave up hurdles when the height increased from 3 foot to 3 foot 3 inches, which didn't suit his running style.\n\nEarly on Wells was aware that he possessed considerable natural spring and was always being tempted to jump and touch over-hanging branches, feeling he could stay up there at the peak of the leap. His father had high jumped at school, and his older brother John had also done so before switching to javelin. In the school library there were two scrapbooks of the 1936 Berlin Olympics, and Wells spent many hours poring over these and, in particular, the high jumping of the American, Harold Osborn, who was the \u201cfather\u201d of the Western Roll technique.\n\nInitially Wells practiced the scissors technique. It probably wasn\u2019t until 1946 or 1947 that he tried  the Western Roll technique, which he later found out to be completely wrong. He also tried the Eastern Cut-Off favoured by Japanese jumpers, but felt you needed to be a contortionist to succeed, although this was the style that Arthur Gold, his future coach, employed.-->\n\n==  English competition highlights ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Height\n!Place\n!Achievement\n!\n|-\n<!--\n|1946 - July 13\n|5 ft 9in\n|2nd\n|AAA Junior Championships<ref>{{Cite news|title=A.A.A Junior Championship|date=11 August 1947|work=Times [London, England]|issue=50836|page=2}}</ref>\n|Birmingham\n|-\n-->\n|1947 - April 19\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|1st\n|First English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n|Motspur Park, London\n|-\n<!--\n|1947 - May 24\n|5 ft 10in\n|1st\n|Herts Schools Champion\n|Barnet, London\n|-\n|1947 - June 28\n|6 ft 1in\n|1st\n|Southern Championships\n|Motspur Park, London\n|-\n|1947 - July 2\n|6 ft 0\u00bcin\n|1st\n|AAA v UAU v Essex & Kent\n|Woodford Bridge\n|-\n|1947 - July 17\n|6 ft 3in\n|2nd\n|England v Wales v Scotland v Ireland\n|Fallowfield, Manchester\n|-\n|1947 - August 4\n|6 ft 1in\n|1st\n|Inter-Counties Championships\n|White City, London\n|-\n-->\n|1947 - August 9\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|1st\n|AAA Junior Championships<ref>{{Cite news|title=A.A.A. Junior Championship|work=Times [London, England]|issue=50836|page=2}}</ref>\n|Fallowfield, Manchester\n|-\n|1947 - August 16\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|3rd\n|BAAB v Combined Services<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics: Olympic Hopes at White City|date=18 August 1947|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=50842|page=6}}</ref>\n|White City, London\n|-\n<!--\n|1948 - May\n|5 ft 8in\n|\n|Herts Champion\n|\n|-\n|1949- June 26\n|6 ft 2in\n|\n|Army Championships\n|Aldershot\n|-\n|1949 - July\n|6 ft 3in\n|\n|Inter-Services Champion\n|\n|-\n-->\n|1949 - August 6\n|6&nbsp;ft 5\u00bcin\n|\n|English Native Record<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n|London\n|-\n|1949 - August 20\n|6&nbsp;ft 6\u00bcin\n|\n|English Native Record<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n|Bristol\n|-\n|1949 - September 4\n|6&nbsp;ft 4in\n|\n|Inter-Services Champion\n|Bourdeaux\n|-\n|1952 - May 17\n|6&nbsp;ft 5in\n|\n|Herts Champion<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics - County Championships|date=19 May 1952|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=52315|page=4}}</ref>\n|New Southgate\n|}\n\n== First English schoolboy to clear {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}} \u2013 1947 ==\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete - 1947 04 18 - London AC Public Schools Challenge Cup - Record - 6ft 0in.jpg|right|thumb|Wells, of Queen Elizabeth's School, becoming the first English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in]]\nWells first big meeting was the Public Schools\u2019 championships of 1946 held on the University of London track at Motspur Park in Surrey, in which he came 3rd with {{convert|5|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Queen Elizabeth's School won the Public Schools Challenge Cup.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|title=Public Schools' Cup|date=21 April 1947|work=The Times|issue=50740|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|title=Public Schools Challenge Cup Meeting at White City|date=8 May 1946|work=The Tatler|issue=2341|volume=CLXXX|page=22}}</ref>\nOn 18 April 1947, the meeting was again at Motspur Park, and this time Wells won the high jump title, in the process becoming the first English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in, beating the previous best of {{convert|5|ft|10.5|in|m|2|abbr=on}} set by H.A.Simmons (Taunton's, Southampton) in 1928.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Record High Jump|date=25 April 1947|work=Illustrated Sporting and Dramatic|issue=3687|volume=183|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=High Jump Record|date=19 April 1947|work=Birmingham Daily Gazette|issue=32116|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Record High Jump by P. Wells|last=Special Correspondent|date=19 April 1947|work=The Daily Telegraph (London, England)}}</ref> Queen Elizabeth's School again won the challenge cup, and as athletics captain Wells had the responsibility of collecting it, plus the high jump cup, in a ceremony at the conclusion of the two-day meeting.<ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Peter Wells Athlete - 1947 - Queen Elizabeths School Athletic Team.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Elizabeth's School athletics team, 1947]]\n\n==  English native high jump record \u2013 1949 ==\n\"English Native Records\" were defined by the [[Amateur Athletic Association of England|AAA]] in 1928 as performances made in England or Wales by athletes born in England or Wales. This was superseded in 1960 by \"AAA National Records\" \u2013 performances made in England or Wales by athletes born in England or Wales, or by bona fide members of clubs under the jurisdiction of the AAA whose fathers were born in England or Wales.\n\n=== {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}} - 6 August 1949, London ===\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 1949.08.06 English Native High Jump Record.jpg|thumb|right|Wells (left) congratulating Ron Pavitt after both jumpers beat the English native high jump record]]\nOn 6 August 1949, high jumpers Wells (20 years old) and Ron Pavitt represented London in an inter-city athletics match against 2 athletes from Gothenburg at [[White City Stadium]], London.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|title=Pavitt Is In World Class|last=Wood|first=Lainson|date=8 August 1949|work=Daily Telegraph (London, England)|issue=29364|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|title=Held Record for Ten Minutes|date=8 August 1949|work=Daily Herald|issue=10428|page=6}}</ref>\n\nUsually Wells would start jumping at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, and increase this by {{convert|0|ft|2|in|cm|0|abbr=on}} after each successful jump. This day the Swedes had to jump first and they passed in at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, and then also at {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Wells and Pavitt also passed in at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}} and {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, so for the first (and only) time in his career Wells started jumping at {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. He and Pavitt succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, then {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, then to  {{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. By this time the Swedish athletes had dropped out. Wells then succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|5.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, at his first attempt, to beat the previous English Native high jump record of {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}} held by [[Benjamin Howard Baker]]. Pavitt also succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|5.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}} to equal the record. At {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}} Pavitt beat the record again, which Wells was unable to match.\n\nSo in the course of about 5 minutes, Wells broke the English Native high jump record, then shared it with Pavitt, and then lost it to Pavitt.\n\nWells and Pavitt maintained a close and friendly rivalry for several years, and were referred to as \"The Heavenly Twins\".\n\n===  6ft. 6\u215cin (1.99m) \u2013 20 August 1949, Bristol ===\nTwo weeks later, Wells and Pavitt competed for the Southern Counties in an inter-area match at St. George Grammar School playing fields at Whitehall, Bristol. Jumping off his preferred grass take-off area, Wells re-took the English Native high jump record with a jump of 6&nbsp;ft. 6\u215cin (1.99m).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|title=New English High Jump Record|last=Special Correspondent|date=22 August 1949|work=Times (London, England)|issue=51466|page=6}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|title=New High Jump Record. Youngster Thrills Bristol Crowd|date=22 August 1949|work=Western Daily Press|page=1}}</ref> This jump was higher than the gold medal jump at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] in London the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1948/ATH/mens-high-jump.html|title=Athletics at the 1948 London Summer Games: Men's High Jump|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> This record was not beaten until 30 April 1959, when the Hermes Club jumper, G.A.Miller, against Oxford University, cleared {{convert|6|ft|7.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}} .<ref>{{Cite news|title=Birchfield Youth Breaks British Junior Record|last=Williams|first=Gron|date=1 May 1959|work=Birmingham Daily Post|issue=31409|page=23}}</ref>\n\n== British high jump record ==\nOn 11 December 1954, in Christchurch, New Zealand, Wells recorded the highest jump of his career with {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> This equalled the British high jump record set by [[Alan Paterson]] on 2 August 1947.<ref name=\"Archive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000769/19470804/082/0006|title=Register {{!}} British Newspaper Archive|last=Archive|first=Coventry Evening Telegraph|date=4 August 1947|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|accessdate=2018-01-15}}</ref> They remained joint British record holders until 1 August 1959 when [[Crawford Fairbrother]] cleared {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Great Glasgow characters|last=John.|first=Burrowes|isbn=9781845966799|location=Edinburgh|oclc=935213681}}</ref>\n\n== Olympic and Commonwealth Games participation ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Event\n!Host City\n!Representing\n!Jump\n!Rank\n|-\n|1950\n|British Empire Games\n|{{flagicon|NZL}} Auckland, New Zealand\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} England\n|{{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BbM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=british+high+jump+records+%22peter+wells%22#v=onepage&q=british+high+jump+records+%22peter+wells%22&f=false|title=The Complete Book of the Commonwealth Games|first=Graham|last=Groom|date=17 October 2017|publisher=Lulu.com|via=Google Books|isbn=9780244940317}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|1952\n|[[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|Olympic Games]]\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} Helsinki, Finland\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain\n|{{convert|1.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|11\n|-\n|1954\n|British Empire and Commonwealth Games\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} Vancouver, Canada\n|{{flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n|{{convert|1.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|4\n|-\n|1956\n|[[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|Olympic Games]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} Melbourne, Australia\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain\n|{{convert|1.96|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|16\n|}\n\n===1950 British Empire Games===\nIn September 1949, the Amateur Athletic Association announced the names of the athletes invited to represent England in the track and field events of the [[1950 British Empire Games|British Empire Games]] in Auckland the following February.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics - Empire Games Team|date=26 September 1949|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=51496|page=6}}</ref> Both Wells and Pavitt were selected.\n\nThe games ran between 4 and 11 February 1950. Coming from an English winter with no available indoor training facilities, and then five weeks on a boat journey to New Zealand was not ideal preparation for Wells. He twisted his ankle on the boat jumping over a net, which set back his training.\n\nThe high jump was held on the first day of competition. The gold medal was won by [[John Winter (athlete)|John Winter]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.com.au/About-Us/Hall-of-Fame/John-Winter|title=John Winter|website=athletics.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> from Australia, with a leap of {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Wells finished fifth, with a best jump of {{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/sports/results.asp?countryid=&resultid=&eventid=1471&sportid=1471&teamid=&catid=133&resultsid=1&gameid=3032&participants=0&categoryid=133&athleteid=&sortid=1 |title=Results for the 1950 British Empire Games \u2013 athletics \u2013 high jump \u2013 men |year=2014 |website= |publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=High Jump Better than Olympics|last=From a Special Correspondent|date=6 February 1950|work=The Daily Telegraph|issue=29518|page=3|type=Article}}</ref>\n\n===1952 Summer Olympics===\nWells represented Great Britain in the [[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|high jump at the 1952 Helsinki Olympics]]. He made it through the qualifying round, jumping {{convert|1.87|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. In the finals, Wells had successful first jumps at {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, but failed on his three attempts at {{convert|1.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, finishing 11th equal out of 28 competitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1952/ATH/mens-high-jump.html|title=Athletics at the 1952 Helsinki Summer Games: Men's High Jump|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games===\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 1954.07 Vancouver.jpg|thumb|Wells practising at Vancouver, 1954|right]]\nIn July 1954, Wells represented New Zealand for the first time, at the [[Athletics at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in Vancouver. He finished fourth, with a height of {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, behind the gold medallist, [[Emmanuel Ifeajuna]] of Nigeria, who set a new [[List of Commonwealth Games records in athletics|Games record]] and [[Commonwealth records in athletics|British Empire record]] of {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/sports/results.asp?countryid=&resultid=&eventid=1471&sportid=1471&teamid=&catid=133&resultsid=1&gameid=3033&participants=0&categoryid=133&athleteid=&sortid=1 |title=Results for the 1954 British Empire & Commonwealth Games \u2013 athletics \u2013 high jump \u2013 men |year=2014 |website= |publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> Wells holding second place until overtaken by two opponents who cleared 6&nbsp;ft 6.25in. (1.99m) with their third and final jumps.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Canterbury's Empire Games Reps Return|date=August 1954|work=The Christchurch Press}}</ref>\n\n=== 1956 Summer Olympics ===\nOlympic eligibility rules meant having already represented Great Britain at the Olympics in Helsinki in 1952, Wells was ineligible to switch his allegiance to New Zealand for the Melbourne Olympics in 1956, even though he had been living in New Zealand for six years. This differed from the eligibility rules for the Empire Games. Wells' good form in domestic competitions in New Zealand during 1956 had not escaped the notice of the Great Britain selectors, and he was duly included in the Great Britain team for the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] in Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Jumping for Britain|date=23 October 1956|work=Lancashire Evening Post|issue=21726|page=7}}</ref>\n\nWells travelled with the New Zealand team to Melbourne, joined up with the Great Britain team on arrival, and travelled back to New Zealand with the New Zealand team at the conclusion of the Games. Later in the Games, when many of the British athletes had left the village, Wells switched camps and moved in with the New Zealand team.\n\nIn the [[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|men's high jump competition]], Wells, progressed through the qualifying rounds, clearing {{convert|1.92|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}. In the final round, he cleared {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.86|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} on his first attempts, and {{convert|1.92|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.96|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} on his second attempts. However, he failed in all three attempts at {{convert|1.96|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}, finishing in 16th place.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/peter-wells-1.html |title=Peter Wells |date= |website=Sports-Reference |publisher= |accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==New Zealand high jump career==\n\n===National records===\nOn 23 January 1954, Wells broke the New Zealand high jump record at Rugby Park in Christchurch with a jump of {{convert|6|ft|6+1/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=N.)|first=Heidenstrom, P. N. (Peter|publisher=GP Publications|year=1992|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=86\u201388|oclc=31711326}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 1954, Wells again broke the New Zealand high jump record at Papakura, Auckland, with a jump of {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> This was to be the highest jump of his career, which equalled the British high jump record set by [[Alan Paterson]] on 2 August 1947.<ref name=\"Archive\"/>\n\nIt was 14 years before the New Zealand record was broken by William R. (Bill) Speirs on 1 March 1969, with a leap of {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=N.)|first=Heidenstrom, P. N. (Peter|date=1992|publisher=GP Publications|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=88|oclc=31711326}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient32061969-t1-body-d25.html|title=Otago Dominates Athletics|date=15 April 1969|work=Salient|access-date=19 January 2018|issue=6|volume=32}}</ref> A year earlier, on 13 January 1968, Arthur W Jordan of Auckland had cleared {{convert|6|ft|7+3/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, but was unable to claim the record because of a technical mistake.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===National champion===\nWells was New Zealand national high jump champion seven times, starting with the 1950\u20131951 season. He did not defend his title the next season, instead returning to England in a successful attempt to represent Great Britain at the 1952 Olympics in Helsinki, but then had a straight run of six titles from the 1952\u20131953 season, through to the 1957\u20131958 season.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://www.anzrankings.org.nz/userfiles/file/National_Champions.pdf |title=National champions 1887\u20132016 |date=December 2016 |website= |publisher=Athletics New Zealand |accessdate=14 January 2018 | first=Stephen | last=Hollings | page=44}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Position\n!Height\n!Venue\n!Representing\n|-\n|1950\u201351\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Wellington\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1951\u201352\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"4\" | Did not defend title\n|-\n|1952\u201353\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|3|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Dunedin\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1953\u201354\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|1|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Hamilton\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1954\u201355\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Auckland\n|Auckland\n|-\n|1955\u201356\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Christchurch\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1956\u201357\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|1|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Napier\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1957\u201358\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Lower Hutt\n|Canterbury\n|}\n<!--\n== Growing up in England ==\nFrom the time he was 2 years old, Wells lived at 36 Byng Road, High Barnet. The youngest of 3, he had a brother John, who was about 3 years older than him, and a sister Mary, who was born between John and Peter. His father, Cecil Edward Wells was a Chartered Accountant, and Company Secretary for an Anglo-Brazilian firm.\n\n'''Second World War'''\n\nWells was 10 when WWII broke out. Barnet received a lot of bombing damage - the German bombers couldn\u2019t get through all the defences around London from the east, so they\u2019d try and come in from the north, come right over Barnet and quite often had to drop their bombs off around Barnet. Queen Elizabeth's School was hit and despite Wells having visions of months and months off school, the school only lost half a day because the bomb only affected the refectory (dining hall) and the chemistry lab.\n\nA bomb also landed in the back yard of 39 Byng Road. The family were lying in the hall which was thought to be the safest place. \u00c1t first it was thought to be an unexploded bomb and the family were evacuated to the local church hall. In fact the bomb did explode, but fortunately the surface was very soft and it exploded deep in the ground and did no damage. If it had exploded on the surface the whole house would have gone.\n\nIn the early days of the bombing, the family would go to an underground shelter in the evening until the bombing stopped. After a while, the family decided to take the risk and stay in the house. Near the end of the war, when [[Doodlebug (flying bomb)|doodlebugs]] were so prominent, Wells' father purchased a [[Morrison shelter|Morrison Shelter]] which was put up in the dining room.\n\n'''Conscription'''\n\nWells was conscripted into the army for 2 years on turning 18 in 1947. He was fortunate to get a London posting - some conscriptees were sent to Korea and died in conflict.\n\n== Emigrating to New Zealand ==\n[[File:1955 02 Cartoon.jpg|thumb|right|Cartoon of Wells from 1955]]\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 2012 05 30 0948 - Peter in blazer.jpg|right|thumb|Wells in 2012, wearing his 1956 British Olympic team blazer]]Wells first arrived in New Zealand as a 20 year old athlete representing England in the high jump at the 1950 [[1950 British Empire Games|British Empire Games]] in Auckland. The only thing Wells knew about the 'colonies' was that once a year his schools had [[Commonwealth Day|Empire Day]], where they were told a little bit about the Empire. There had been a suggestion during the war years that all school children be evacuated, and Wells had wanted to go to Australia because it was furthest away.\n\nWells had completed his 2 years compulsory service in the army, had plans to follow his father's career as an Accountant, had secured a job as an Articles Clerk with a firm of London Accountants, and was part way through his Articles at the time of selection.\n\nAt the time England was still had severe food rationing. One of the big impressions New Zealand made on Wells was the magnificent food readily available - beautiful meat, cream, milk, ice cream and jugs of fruit juice.\n\nAfter the Games, while waiting for the Tamaroa to arrive to take them back to England, the English team split and went on an athletics tour of New Zealand. The group Wells was with travelled by train from Auckland to Wellington stooping at Rotorua on the way where they were hosted and entertained by the local Maori. From Wellington, they caught the inter-island ferry to Lyttelton, the port town that services Christchurch. They competed in Invercargill, Dunedin, Timaru, Christchurch, Nelson and Wellington. In Christchurch, Wells and Ron Pavitt stayed with Tick Langford, who was the public relations officer looking after the team. When the rest of the team got on the Tamaroa to head back to England, Wells had already decided that he wanted to stay, and caught the ferry back to Lyttelton instead.\n\nThe Langfords met Wells at Lyttelton and offered him a  place to stay in Christchurch, and shortly after he got offered a clerical job with McKendrick Brothers, a sack and jute merchant. He sent a telegram to his parents asking for their permission to stay in New Zealand, and requested a release from his Articles of Association - both of which were duly received.\n\nAs well as the food, Wells was attracted to the kiwi way of life. He was very aware of the class consciousness back in England, the University/non-University divide, and the tremendous gap between the rich and the poor. He also didn't want to go back to environment he'd been in - an hour on the tube every morning to work, standing on the tube halfway home because it was so crowded. He liked the open spaces New Zealand had to offer, and found Kiwi's to be 'free and easy'.  Wells realised that if he were to go back to the UK, it would take him years to save up enough money to get back to New Zealand.\n\nWells was not the only English athlete to stay behind. [[Harold Moody (athlete)|Dr Harold (HEA) Moody]] the shot putter, [[John Parlett]] (middle distance runner), [[Leslie Lewis (sprinter)|Leslie Charles Lewis]] (220 and 440 yards), and [[Duncan Clark (athlete)|Duncan (D.McD,D) Clark]] (Hammer Throw) also settled in New Zealand after the [[1950 British Empire Games|1950 Empire Games]].\n\nIn 1952 he married Shirley Muriel Grimwood from Harwarden, North Canterbury, and currently has 5 children, 10 grandchildren, and 8 great-grandchildren.\n-->== Jumping technique \u2013 the Western roll ==\nWells used the [[Western roll]] jumping technique.\n\nPeter Heidenstrom, athletics commentator and historian,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=Heidenstrom|first=P. N. (Peter)|date=1992|publisher=GP Publications|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=Back Cover|oclc=31711326}}</ref> described Wells' Western roll as \"finely controlled, precise, a beautiful thing to watch\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Englishmen Should Head NZAAA Championships. Clark, Moody, Lewis and Wells Will Trouble New Zealand's Best|last=Heidenstrom|first=P. N. (Peter)|date=19 February 1953|work=All-Sports|page=48}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1954 New Zealand British Empire and Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC high jump men}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, Peter}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male high jumpers]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1950 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Peter Wells\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = 1949 08 06 Peter Wells.jpg\n| image_size = <!-- only when absolutely necessary -->\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| headercolor = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name = <!-- if different than name -->\n| full_name = Peter Wells\n| nickname = \n| nationality =  English, New Zealand \n| national_team = \n| ethnicity = \n| citizenship = \n| birth_date = {{birth date|1929|05|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Friern Barnet]], London\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1929|05|23|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments = \n| education = Byng Road Council School, [[Queen Elizabeth's School, Barnet]]\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| agent = \n| height = {{convert|5|ft|11.5|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| weight = <!-- X kg, X lb, or X st Y lb (automatic conversion) plus optional year and reference -->\n| spouse = \n| life_partner = \n| other_interests = \n| website = {{URL|www.peterwells.co.nz}}\n| country = {{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain<br/>{{flagicon|ENG}} England<br/>{{flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n| sport = Athletics\n| position = \n| disability = \n| disability_class = \n| weight_class = \n| weight_class_type = \n| rank = \n| event = High Jump\n| universityteam = \n| collegeteam = \n| league = \n| league_type = \n| club = \n| team = \n| turnedpro = \n| partner = \n| former_partner = \n| coach = Arthur Gold\n| retired = \n| coaching = \n| worlds = \n| regionals = \n| nationals = \n| olympics = [[1952 Summer Olympics]] [[1956 Summer Olympics]]\n| paralympics = \n| commonwealth = [[1950 British Empire Games]] [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n| highestranking = \n| pb = {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals = \n| medaltemplates-title = \n}}\n'''Peter Wells''' (23 May 1929 \u2013 5 January 2018) was a British-born athlete who competed in the High Jump at the [[1952 Summer Olympics|1952]] and [[1956 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{Cite sports-reference | Peter Wells | https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/peter-wells-1.html| 15 July 2017 }}</ref>\n\nHe also represented England at the [[1950 British Empire Games|1950 Empire Games]] in Auckland, and New Zealand at the [[1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1954 Commonwealth Games]] in Vancouver. After the 1950 Empire Games in Auckland, Wells didn't travel back to England with the rest of the team, preferring to stay and settle in Christchurch, New Zealand. He lived in New Zealand for the rest of his life, apart from a short period in 1952 when he returned to England in order to qualify for the 1952 Summer Olympics. He died in Christchurch on 5 January 2018 after a short illness.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deaths.press.co.nz/obituaries/the-press-nz/obituary.aspx?n=peter-wells&pid=187773049|title=Peter Wells death notice|date=9 January 2018|work=[[The Press]]|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/athletics/news/article.cfm?c_id=19&objectid=11979633|title=Athletics NZ weekly roundup 22 January 2018|date=22 January 2018|work=New Zealand Herald|access-date=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/101236222/life-story-humble-olympian-peter-wells-flew-high-and-stayed-grounded|title=Life story: Humble Olympian Peter Wells flew high and stayed grounded|last=Northcott|first=Maddison|date=10 February 2018|work=The Christchurch Press|access-date=10 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nWells was born at [[Friern Barnet]] in North London, the youngest child of Cecil Edward Wells and Ethel Alice Wells (n\u00e9e Cannon). He lived initially in [[Finchley]] before moving at the age of two to [[High Barnet]]. He attended Byng Road Council School, (now called [http://www.fouldsp.org/about-our-school/history Foulds School]), and then went to [[Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School, Barnet|Queen Elizabeth's Grammar School]] in 1939.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/achievements/national_and_international_honours_list|title=Queen Elizabeth's School - National and international honours list|website=www.qebarnet.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qebarnet.co.uk/peters_olympic_memories|title=Peter's Olympic memories|date=2015|website=Queen Elizabeth's School|access-date=18 January 2018}}</ref> \n<!--\n== Early interest in athletics ==\n[[File:193x - Peter Wells Athlete - DOB 1929.05.23.jpg|left|upright=0.65|thumb|Wells as a boy]]\nWells first remembers competing in athletics whilst at Byng Road Council School - participating  in inter-schools\u2019 sports at the Barnet Playing Fields at the bottom of Barnet Hill, in Hertfordshire. The only events at that time were sprints, and Wells was usually able to win his age group.\n\nIn September 1939 Wells went to Queen Elizabeth\u2019s Grammar School for boys, in Barnet, and participated in the annual inter-house athletics, again initially, in short sprints. At some stage he switched to concentrating on high jump and hurdles, in which he represented his school at the County schools\u2019 meeting in 1944, and then the Public Schools\u2019 championships at the White City Stadium, in London. Queen Elizabeth\u2019s had won the team event at those championships in 1939 and there was therefore quite a tradition of athletics at the school. This was probably due mainly to the enthusiasm and coaching of \u201cKlue\u201d (K.L. Woodland), the German language teacher.\n\nHe gave up hurdles when the height increased from 3 foot to 3 foot 3 inches, which didn't suit his running style.\n\nEarly on Wells was aware that he possessed considerable natural spring and was always being tempted to jump and touch over-hanging branches, feeling he could stay up there at the peak of the leap. His father had high jumped at school, and his older brother John had also done so before switching to javelin. In the school library there were two scrapbooks of the 1936 Berlin Olympics, and Wells spent many hours poring over these and, in particular, the high jumping of the American, Harold Osborn, who was the \u201cfather\u201d of the Western Roll technique.\n\nInitially Wells practiced the scissors technique. It probably wasn\u2019t until 1946 or 1947 that he tried  the Western Roll technique, which he later found out to be completely wrong. He also tried the Eastern Cut-Off favoured by Japanese jumpers, but felt you needed to be a contortionist to succeed, although this was the style that Arthur Gold, his future coach, employed.-->\n\n==  English competition highlights ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Height\n!Place\n!Achievement\n!\n|-\n<!--\n|1946 - July 13\n|5 ft 9in\n|2nd\n|AAA Junior Championships<ref>{{Cite news|title=A.A.A Junior Championship|date=11 August 1947|work=Times [London, England]|issue=50836|page=2}}</ref>\n|Birmingham\n|-\n-->\n|1947 - April 19\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|1st\n|First English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n|Motspur Park, London\n|-\n<!--\n|1947 - May 24\n|5 ft 10in\n|1st\n|Herts Schools Champion\n|Barnet, London\n|-\n|1947 - June 28\n|6 ft 1in\n|1st\n|Southern Championships\n|Motspur Park, London\n|-\n|1947 - July 2\n|6 ft 0\u00bcin\n|1st\n|AAA v UAU v Essex & Kent\n|Woodford Bridge\n|-\n|1947 - July 17\n|6 ft 3in\n|2nd\n|England v Wales v Scotland v Ireland\n|Fallowfield, Manchester\n|-\n|1947 - August 4\n|6 ft 1in\n|1st\n|Inter-Counties Championships\n|White City, London\n|-\n-->\n|1947 - August 9\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|1st\n|AAA Junior Championships<ref>{{Cite news|title=A.A.A. Junior Championship|work=Times [London, England]|issue=50836|page=2}}</ref>\n|Fallowfield, Manchester\n|-\n|1947 - August 16\n|6&nbsp;ft 0in\n|3rd\n|BAAB v Combined Services<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics: Olympic Hopes at White City|date=18 August 1947|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=50842|page=6}}</ref>\n|White City, London\n|-\n<!--\n|1948 - May\n|5 ft 8in\n|\n|Herts Champion\n|\n|-\n|1949- June 26\n|6 ft 2in\n|\n|Army Championships\n|Aldershot\n|-\n|1949 - July\n|6 ft 3in\n|\n|Inter-Services Champion\n|\n|-\n-->\n|1949 - August 6\n|6&nbsp;ft 5\u00bcin\n|\n|English Native Record<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" />\n|London\n|-\n|1949 - August 20\n|6&nbsp;ft 6\u00bcin\n|\n|English Native Record<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" />\n|Bristol\n|-\n|1949 - September 4\n|6&nbsp;ft 4in\n|\n|Inter-Services Champion\n|Bourdeaux\n|-\n|1952 - May 17\n|6&nbsp;ft 5in\n|\n|Herts Champion<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics - County Championships|date=19 May 1952|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=52315|page=4}}</ref>\n|New Southgate\n|}\n\n== First English schoolboy to clear {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}} \u2013 1947 ==\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete - 1947 04 18 - London AC Public Schools Challenge Cup - Record - 6ft 0in.jpg|right|thumb|Wells, of Queen Elizabeth's School, becoming the first English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in]]\nWells first big meeting was the Public Schools\u2019 championships of 1946 held on the University of London track at Motspur Park in Surrey, in which he came 3rd with {{convert|5|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Queen Elizabeth's School won the Public Schools Challenge Cup.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|title=Public Schools' Cup|date=21 April 1947|work=The Times|issue=50740|page=2}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|title=Public Schools Challenge Cup Meeting at White City|date=8 May 1946|work=The Tatler|issue=2341|volume=CLXXX|page=22}}</ref>\nOn 18 April 1947, the meeting was again at Motspur Park, and this time Wells won the high jump title, in the process becoming the first English schoolboy to clear 6&nbsp;ft 0in, beating the previous best of {{convert|5|ft|10.5|in|m|2|abbr=on}} set by H.A.Simmons (Taunton's, Southampton) in 1928.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Record High Jump|date=25 April 1947|work=Illustrated Sporting and Dramatic|issue=3687|volume=183|page=26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=High Jump Record|date=19 April 1947|work=Birmingham Daily Gazette|issue=32116|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Record High Jump by P. Wells|last=Special Correspondent|date=19 April 1947|work=The Daily Telegraph (London, England)}}</ref> Queen Elizabeth's School again won the challenge cup, and as athletics captain Wells had the responsibility of collecting it, plus the high jump cup, in a ceremony at the conclusion of the two-day meeting.<ref name=\":2\" />[[File:Peter Wells Athlete - 1947 - Queen Elizabeths School Athletic Team.jpg|thumb|right|Queen Elizabeth's School athletics team, 1947]]\n\n==  English native high jump record \u2013 1949 ==\n\"English Native Records\" were defined by the [[Amateur Athletic Association of England|AAA]] in 1928 as performances made in England or Wales by athletes born in England or Wales. This was superseded in 1960 by \"AAA National Records\" \u2013 performances made in England or Wales by athletes born in England or Wales, or by bona fide members of clubs under the jurisdiction of the AAA whose fathers were born in England or Wales.\n\n=== {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}} - 6 August 1949, London ===\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 1949.08.06 English Native High Jump Record.jpg|thumb|right|Wells (left) congratulating Ron Pavitt after both jumpers beat the English native high jump record]]\nOn 6 August 1949, high jumpers Wells (20 years old) and Ron Pavitt represented London in an inter-city athletics match against 2 athletes from Gothenburg at [[White City Stadium]], London.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|title=Pavitt Is In World Class|last=Wood|first=Lainson|date=8 August 1949|work=Daily Telegraph (London, England)|issue=29364|page=3}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|title=Held Record for Ten Minutes|date=8 August 1949|work=Daily Herald|issue=10428|page=6}}</ref>\n\nUsually Wells would start jumping at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, and increase this by {{convert|0|ft|2|in|cm|0|abbr=on}} after each successful jump. This day the Swedes had to jump first and they passed in at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, and then also at {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Wells and Pavitt also passed in at {{convert|5|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}} and {{convert|5|ft|10|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, so for the first (and only) time in his career Wells started jumping at {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. He and Pavitt succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, then {{convert|6|ft|2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, then to  {{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. By this time the Swedish athletes had dropped out. Wells then succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|5.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, at his first attempt, to beat the previous English Native high jump record of {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}} held by [[Benjamin Howard Baker]]. Pavitt also succeeded at {{convert|6|ft|5.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}} to equal the record. At {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}} Pavitt beat the record again, which Wells was unable to match.\n\nSo in the course of about 5 minutes, Wells broke the English Native high jump record, then shared it with Pavitt, and then lost it to Pavitt.\n\nWells and Pavitt maintained a close and friendly rivalry for several years, and were referred to as \"The Heavenly Twins\".\n\n===  6ft. 6\u215cin (1.99m) \u2013 20 August 1949, Bristol ===\nTwo weeks later, Wells and Pavitt competed for the Southern Counties in an inter-area match at St. George Grammar School playing fields at Whitehall, Bristol. Jumping off his preferred grass take-off area, Wells re-took the English Native high jump record with a jump of 6&nbsp;ft. 6\u215cin (1.99m).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|title=New English High Jump Record|last=Special Correspondent|date=22 August 1949|work=Times (London, England)|issue=51466|page=6}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|title=New High Jump Record. Youngster Thrills Bristol Crowd|date=22 August 1949|work=Western Daily Press|page=1}}</ref> This jump was higher than the gold medal jump at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] in London the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1948/ATH/mens-high-jump.html|title=Athletics at the 1948 London Summer Games: Men's High Jump|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> This record was not beaten until 30 April 1959, when the Hermes Club jumper, G.A.Miller, against Oxford University, cleared {{convert|6|ft|7.25|in|m|2|abbr=on}} .<ref>{{Cite news|title=Birchfield Youth Breaks British Junior Record|last=Williams|first=Gron|date=1 May 1959|work=Birmingham Daily Post|issue=31409|page=23}}</ref>\n\n== British high jump record ==\nOn 11 December 1954, in Christchurch, New Zealand, Wells recorded the highest jump of his career with {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> This equalled the British high jump record set by [[Alan Paterson]] on 2 August 1947.<ref name=\"Archive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000769/19470804/082/0006|title=Register {{!}} British Newspaper Archive|last=Archive|first=Coventry Evening Telegraph|date=4 August 1947|website=www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk|accessdate=2018-01-15}}</ref> They remained joint British record holders until 1 August 1959 when [[Crawford Fairbrother]] cleared {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Great Glasgow characters|last=John.|first=Burrowes|isbn=9781845966799|location=Edinburgh|oclc=935213681}}</ref>\n\n== Olympic and Commonwealth Games participation ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Event\n!Host City\n!Representing\n!Jump\n!Rank\n|-\n|1950\n|British Empire Games\n|{{flagicon|NZL}} Auckland, New Zealand\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} England\n|{{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|order=flip|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BbM7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&dq=british+high+jump+records+%22peter+wells%22#v=onepage&q=british+high+jump+records+%22peter+wells%22&f=false|title=The Complete Book of the Commonwealth Games|first=Graham|last=Groom|date=17 October 2017|publisher=Lulu.com|via=Google Books|isbn=9780244940317}}</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|1952\n|[[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|Olympic Games]]\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} Helsinki, Finland\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain\n|{{convert|1.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|11\n|-\n|1954\n|British Empire and Commonwealth Games\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} Vancouver, Canada\n|{{flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n|{{convert|1.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|4\n|-\n|1956\n|[[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|Olympic Games]]\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} Melbourne, Australia\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Great Britain\n|{{convert|1.96|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|16\n|}\n\n===1950 British Empire Games===\nIn September 1949, the Amateur Athletic Association announced the names of the athletes invited to represent England in the track and field events of the [[1950 British Empire Games|British Empire Games]] in Auckland the following February.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Athletics - Empire Games Team|date=26 September 1949|work=The Times [London, England]|issue=51496|page=6}}</ref> Both Wells and Pavitt were selected.\n\nThe games ran between 4 and 11 February 1950. Coming from an English winter with no available indoor training facilities, and then five weeks on a boat journey to New Zealand was not ideal preparation for Wells. He twisted his ankle on the boat jumping over a net, which set back his training.\n\nThe high jump was held on the first day of competition. The gold medal was won by [[John Winter (athlete)|John Winter]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.com.au/About-Us/Hall-of-Fame/John-Winter|title=John Winter|website=athletics.com.au|language=en-AU|access-date=2018-01-14}}</ref> from Australia, with a leap of {{convert|6|ft|6|in|m|2|abbr=on}}. Wells finished fifth, with a best jump of {{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/sports/results.asp?countryid=&resultid=&eventid=1471&sportid=1471&teamid=&catid=133&resultsid=1&gameid=3032&participants=0&categoryid=133&athleteid=&sortid=1 |title=Results for the 1950 British Empire Games \u2013 athletics \u2013 high jump \u2013 men |year=2014 |website= |publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=High Jump Better than Olympics|last=From a Special Correspondent|date=6 February 1950|work=The Daily Telegraph|issue=29518|page=3|type=Article}}</ref>\n\n===1952 Summer Olympics===\nWells represented Great Britain in the [[Athletics at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|high jump at the 1952 Helsinki Olympics]]. He made it through the qualifying round, jumping {{convert|1.87|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. In the finals, Wells had successful first jumps at {{convert|1.70|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.90|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, but failed on his three attempts at {{convert|1.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, finishing 11th equal out of 28 competitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1952/ATH/mens-high-jump.html|title=Athletics at the 1952 Helsinki Summer Games: Men's High Jump|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games===\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 1954.07 Vancouver.jpg|thumb|Wells practising at Vancouver, 1954|right]]\nIn July 1954, Wells represented New Zealand for the first time, at the [[Athletics at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in Vancouver. He finished fourth, with a height of {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, behind the gold medallist, [[Emmanuel Ifeajuna]] of Nigeria, who set a new [[List of Commonwealth Games records in athletics|Games record]] and [[Commonwealth records in athletics|British Empire record]] of {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecgf.com/sports/results.asp?countryid=&resultid=&eventid=1471&sportid=1471&teamid=&catid=133&resultsid=1&gameid=3033&participants=0&categoryid=133&athleteid=&sortid=1 |title=Results for the 1954 British Empire & Commonwealth Games \u2013 athletics \u2013 high jump \u2013 men |year=2014 |website= |publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation |accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> Wells holding second place until overtaken by two opponents who cleared 6&nbsp;ft 6.25in. (1.99m) with their third and final jumps.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Canterbury's Empire Games Reps Return|date=August 1954|work=The Christchurch Press}}</ref>\n\n=== 1956 Summer Olympics ===\nOlympic eligibility rules meant having already represented Great Britain at the Olympics in Helsinki in 1952, Wells was ineligible to switch his allegiance to New Zealand for the Melbourne Olympics in 1956, even though he had been living in New Zealand for six years. This differed from the eligibility rules for the Empire Games. Wells' good form in domestic competitions in New Zealand during 1956 had not escaped the notice of the Great Britain selectors, and he was duly included in the Great Britain team for the [[1956 Summer Olympics]] in Melbourne.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Jumping for Britain|date=23 October 1956|work=Lancashire Evening Post|issue=21726|page=7}}</ref>\n\nWells travelled with the New Zealand team to Melbourne, joined up with the Great Britain team on arrival, and travelled back to New Zealand with the New Zealand team at the conclusion of the Games. Later in the Games, when many of the British athletes had left the village, Wells switched camps and moved in with the New Zealand team.\n\nIn the [[Athletics at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's high jump|men's high jump competition]], Wells, progressed through the qualifying rounds, clearing {{convert|1.92|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}. In the final round, he cleared {{convert|1.80|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.86|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} on his first attempts, and {{convert|1.92|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|1.96|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}} on his second attempts. However, he failed in all three attempts at {{convert|1.96|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}, finishing in 16th place.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/we/peter-wells-1.html |title=Peter Wells |date= |website=Sports-Reference |publisher= |accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==New Zealand high jump career==\n\n===National records===\nOn 23 January 1954, Wells broke the New Zealand high jump record at Rugby Park in Christchurch with a jump of {{convert|6|ft|6+1/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=N.)|first=Heidenstrom, P. N. (Peter|publisher=GP Publications|year=1992|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=86\u201388|oclc=31711326}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 December 1954, Wells again broke the New Zealand high jump record at Papakura, Auckland, with a jump of {{convert|6|ft|7+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> This was to be the highest jump of his career, which equalled the British high jump record set by [[Alan Paterson]] on 2 August 1947.<ref name=\"Archive\"/>\n\nIt was 14 years before the New Zealand record was broken by William R. (Bill) Speirs on 1 March 1969, with a leap of {{convert|6|ft|8|in|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=N.)|first=Heidenstrom, P. N. (Peter|date=1992|publisher=GP Publications|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=88|oclc=31711326}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Salient32061969-t1-body-d25.html|title=Otago Dominates Athletics|date=15 April 1969|work=Salient|access-date=19 January 2018|issue=6|volume=32}}</ref> A year earlier, on 13 January 1968, Arthur W Jordan of Auckland had cleared {{convert|6|ft|7+3/4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}, but was unable to claim the record because of a technical mistake.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n===National champion===\nWells was New Zealand national high jump champion seven times, starting with the 1950-1951 season. He did not defend his title the next season, instead returning to England in a successful attempt to represent Great Britain at the 1952 Olympics in Helsinki, but then had a straight run of six titles from the 1952-1953 season, through to the 1957-1958 season.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://www.anzrankings.org.nz/userfiles/file/National_Champions.pdf |title=National champions 1887\u20132016 |date=December 2016 |website= |publisher=Athletics New Zealand |accessdate=14 January 2018 | first=Stephen | last=Hollings | page=44}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Season\n!Position\n!Height\n!Venue\n!Representing\n|-\n|1950\u201351\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|4|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Wellington\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1951\u201352\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"4\" | Did not defend title\n|-\n|1952\u201353\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|3|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Dunedin\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1953\u201354\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|1|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Hamilton\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1954\u201355\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Auckland\n|Auckland\n|-\n|1955\u201356\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|7|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Christchurch\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1956\u201357\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|1|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Napier\n|Canterbury\n|-\n|1957\u201358\n|1st\n|{{convert|6|ft|5|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|Lower Hutt\n|Canterbury\n|}\n<!--\n== Growing up in England ==\nFrom the time he was 2 years old, Wells lived at 36 Byng Road, High Barnet. The youngest of 3, he had a brother John, who was about 3 years older than him, and a sister Mary, who was born between John and Peter. His father, Cecil Edward Wells was a Chartered Accountant, and Company Secretary for an Anglo-Brazilian firm.\n\n'''Second World War'''\n\nWells was 10 when WWII broke out. Barnet received a lot of bombing damage - the German bombers couldn\u2019t get through all the defences around London from the east, so they\u2019d try and come in from the north, come right over Barnet and quite often had to drop their bombs off around Barnet. Queen Elizabeth's School was hit and despite Wells having visions of months and months off school, the school only lost half a day because the bomb only affected the refectory (dining hall) and the chemistry lab.\n\nA bomb also landed in the back yard of 39 Byng Road. The family were lying in the hall which was thought to be the safest place. \u00c1t first it was thought to be an unexploded bomb and the family were evacuated to the local church hall. In fact the bomb did explode, but fortunately the surface was very soft and it exploded deep in the ground and did no damage. If it had exploded on the surface the whole house would have gone.\n\nIn the early days of the bombing, the family would go to an underground shelter in the evening until the bombing stopped. After a while, the family decided to take the risk and stay in the house. Near the end of the war, when [[Doodlebug (flying bomb)|doodlebugs]] were so prominent, Wells' father purchased a [[Morrison shelter|Morrison Shelter]] which was put up in the dining room.\n\n'''Conscription'''\n\nWells was conscripted into the army for 2 years on turning 18 in 1947. He was fortunate to get a London posting - some conscriptees were sent to Korea and died in conflict.\n\n== Emigrating to New Zealand ==\n[[File:1955 02 Cartoon.jpg|thumb|right|Cartoon of Wells from 1955]]\n[[File:Peter Wells Athlete 2012 05 30 0948 - Peter in blazer.jpg|right|thumb|Wells in 2012, wearing his 1956 British Olympic team blazer]]Wells first arrived in New Zealand as a 20 year old athlete representing England in the high jump at the 1950 [[1950 British Empire Games|British Empire Games]] in Auckland. The only thing Wells knew about the 'colonies' was that once a year his schools had [[Commonwealth Day|Empire Day]], where they were told a little bit about the Empire. There had been a suggestion during the war years that all school children be evacuated, and Wells had wanted to go to Australia because it was furthest away.\n\nWells had completed his 2 years compulsory service in the army, had plans to follow his father's career as an Accountant, had secured a job as an Articles Clerk with a firm of London Accountants, and was part way through his Articles at the time of selection.\n\nAt the time England was still had severe food rationing. One of the big impressions New Zealand made on Wells was the magnificent food readily available - beautiful meat, cream, milk, ice cream and jugs of fruit juice.\n\nAfter the Games, while waiting for the Tamaroa to arrive to take them back to England, the English team split and went on an athletics tour of New Zealand. The group Wells was with travelled by train from Auckland to Wellington stooping at Rotorua on the way where they were hosted and entertained by the local Maori. From Wellington, they caught the inter-island ferry to Lyttelton, the port town that services Christchurch. They competed in Invercargill, Dunedin, Timaru, Christchurch, Nelson and Wellington. In Christchurch, Wells and Ron Pavitt stayed with Tick Langford, who was the public relations officer looking after the team. When the rest of the team got on the Tamaroa to head back to England, Wells had already decided that he wanted to stay, and caught the ferry back to Lyttelton instead.\n\nThe Langfords met Wells at Lyttelton and offered him a  place to stay in Christchurch, and shortly after he got offered a clerical job with McKendrick Brothers, a sack and jute merchant. He sent a telegram to his parents asking for their permission to stay in New Zealand, and requested a release from his Articles of Association - both of which were duly received.\n\nAs well as the food, Wells was attracted to the kiwi way of life. He was very aware of the class consciousness back in England, the University/non-University divide, and the tremendous gap between the rich and the poor. He also didn't want to go back to environment he'd been in - an hour on the tube every morning to work, standing on the tube halfway home because it was so crowded. He liked the open spaces New Zealand had to offer, and found Kiwi's to be 'free and easy'.  Wells realised that if he were to go back to the UK, it would take him years to save up enough money to get back to New Zealand.\n\nWells was not the only English athlete to stay behind. [[Harold Moody (athlete)|Dr Harold (HEA) Moody]] the shot putter, [[John Parlett]] (middle distance runner), [[Leslie Lewis (sprinter)|Leslie Charles Lewis]] (220 and 440 yards), and [[Duncan Clark (athlete)|Duncan (D.McD,D) Clark]] (Hammer Throw) also settled in New Zealand after the [[1950 British Empire Games|1950 Empire Games]].\n\nIn 1952 he married Shirley Muriel Grimwood from Harwarden, North Canterbury, and currently has 5 children, 10 grandchildren, and 8 great-grandchildren.\n-->== Jumping technique \u2013 the Western roll ==\nWells used the [[Western roll]] jumping technique.\n\nPeter Heidenstrom, athletics commentator and historian,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Athletes of the century : 100 years of New Zealand track and field|last=Heidenstrom|first=P. N. (Peter)|date=1992|publisher=GP Publications|isbn=1869560442|location=Wellington, N.Z.|pages=Back Cover|oclc=31711326}}</ref> described Wells' Western roll as \"finely controlled, precise, a beautiful thing to watch\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Englishmen Should Head NZAAA Championships. Clark, Moody, Lewis and Wells Will Trouble New Zealand's Best|last=Heidenstrom|first=P. N. (Peter)|date=19 February 1953|work=All-Sports|page=48}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1954 New Zealand British Empire and Commonwealth Games team}}\n{{Footer New Zealand NC high jump men}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wells, Peter}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male high jumpers]]\n[[Category:People from the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Olympic athletes of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1950 British Empire Games]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1954 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games competitors for New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNational champion:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1950-1951 \u2192 1950\u20131951 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Wells_(athlete)"}
{"title_page": "Aasif Sheikh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aasif Sheikh\n| image              = Aasif Sheikh.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = <!--Birthdate must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs. No IMDb. No public records. See WP:BLPPRIVACY-->\n| birth_place        = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = Film and television actor}}\n| yearsactive        = 1984 \u2013 present<ref name=\"Bhabhi Ji Ghar Par Hain\u2019s Aasif Sheikh aka Vibhuti Narayan on rewind\">{{cite news | url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/bhabhi-ji-ghar-par-hains-aasif-sheikh-aka-vibhuti-narayan-on-rewind/ | title=Bhabhi Ji Ghar Par Hain's Aasif Sheikh aka Vibhuti Narayan on rewind | work= Bollywood Life |author=Urmimala Banerjee |date=9 June 2016 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n| known_for          = ''[[Bhabi Ji Ghar Par Hai!]]''<br/>''[[Yes Boss (TV series)|Yes Boss]]''<br>''[[Karan Arjun]]''<br>''[[Yaara Dildara]]''<br>''[[Rama O Rama]]''\n| website            = \n| spouse             =  Zeba Sheikh\n|children= 2\n| home_town          = [[Varanasi]], India\n}}\n\n'''Aasif Sheikh''' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] film, stage and television actor. He played the role of Prince Ajay Singh in India's first TV serial, ''[[Hum Log (TV series)|Hum Log]]''. He has appeared in numerous Bollywood films and TV serials. He acted in the TV series [[Yes Boss (TV series)|Yes Boss]] which ran from 1999 to 2009. Presently running sitcom series ''[[Bhabiji Ghar Par Hain!]]'', has him playing the role of ''Vibhuti Narayan Mishra''.\n\n==Personal life==\nSheikh spent his childhood in [[Varanasi]], [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url =https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/events/lucknow/my-cousins-considered-me-a-dud-actor-aasif-sheikh/articleshow/62085654.cms|title =My cousins considered me a dud actor: Aasif Sheikh|work =[[The Times of India]] |author=Meera Vohra |date=16 December 2016 |accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> He is married to Zeba Sheikh, with whom he has two children, daughter Maryam Nastasia and son Alyjah Iman.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u092f\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 '\u092d\u093e\u092c\u0940\u091c\u0940...' \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u092d\u0942\u0924\u093f \u0928\u093e\u0930\u093e\u092f\u0923 \u0915\u0940 \u092c\u0947\u091f\u0940, \u0926\u0947\u0916\u0947\u0902 Family \u0915\u0940 Unseen Photos |url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/ent-tv-bhabi-ji-ghar-par-hai-actor-aashif-sheikh-unseen-family-photos-news-hindi-5529502-pho.html |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=Dainik Bhaskar |date=16 February 2017 |language=hi}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=iaasifsheikh |number =695124434751852544 |title=@Neeshasharma7 my son..Alyjah Iman...daughter..Maryam Nastassia...|date=3 February 2016 |accessdate=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Theatre==\n\nHe is associated with Indian People's Theatre Association, Mumbai. He has acted in plays like ''[[Kabuliwala (short story)|Kabuliwala]]'', ''Aakhri Shama'', ''Simla Coffee House'', ''Hum Deewane Hum Parwane'', ''Ek Baar Phir'' and ''Aaall izz Well with Shuturmurgh''. One of his popular plays is ''U-Turn'' co-starring [[Poonam Dhillon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=INDIAN PEOPLE'S THEATRE ASSOCIATION - Plays |url=http://www.iptamumbai.in/Plays |website=IPTAMumbai |accessdate=2 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nSheikh started his career with ''[[Hum Log (TV series)|Hum Log]]'', India's first daily television show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailypost.in/lifestyle/fashion-and-beauty/49738-a-straightforward-man |title=A Straightforward Man |website=[[Daily Post India]] |author=Daily Life writer |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=28 December 2018 |url-stat